====== C++ STANDARDS REFERENCE ======

1. C++98 — ISO/IEC 14882:1998 ⭐
First international C++ standard.
Key features:
Classes, objects, templates
Exceptions
Operator overloading
Namespaces
Standard Template Library (STL): vector, map, list, string, etc.
iostreams
Runtime type information (RTTI)

2. C++03 — ISO/IEC 14882:2003
Bug-fix revision of C++98.
Key features:
Fixes to template rules
Improvements to the standard library
No major new language features

3. C++11 — ISO/IEC 14882:2011
Massive modernization of C++.
Often called C++0x or the “modern C++ revolution”.
Key features:
auto type deduction
range-based for loops
lambda expressions
move semantics (&&, rvalue references)
smart pointers (shared_ptr, unique_ptr)
std::thread, mutexes, and futures
constexpr
nullptr, strong enums
uniform initialization {}
variadic templates

New STL containers: unordered_map, array, forward_list
4. C++14 — ISO/IEC 14882:2014
Minor improvement of C++11.
Key features:
Generic lambdas
Relaxed constexpr
make_unique
Binary literals (0b1010)
Return type deduction

5. C++17 — ISO/IEC 14882:2017
Simplification & library expansion.
Key features:
std::optional, std::variant, std::any
std::filesystem
if/switch with initializer
structured bindings (auto [x, y] = …)
inline variables
std::string_view
Parallel algorithms
Folding expressions for templates

6. C++20 — ISO/IEC 14882:2020
One of the biggest updates after C++11.
Key features:
Concepts
Ranges library
Coroutines (co_await, co_yield)
Modules (import, export)
Three-way comparison operator <=>
Calendar & timezone library
std::span
constexpr improvements (even for std::vector in some implementations)

7. C++23 — ISO/IEC 14882:2024
Newest finalized standard (published 2024).
Key features:
std::expected
std::print (finally!)
Pattern matching (partial)
Expanded ranges: views::join_with, zip, etc.
constexpr for more library components
Improved Unicode support
std::mdspan
Networking TS not included, postponed

8. Design Patterns
Singleton Pattern
Ensures a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access. Useful for hardware resource management (e.g., a single UART driver).

Factory Pattern
Creates objects without specifying the exact class. Useful for abstracting hardware interfaces or device drivers.

Observer Pattern
Allows objects to be notified of state changes in other objects. Useful for event-driven systems (e.g., sensor updates).

State Pattern ⭐⭐⭐
Encapsulates state-specific behavior. Useful for implementing state machines common in embedded systems.
Audio use: Playback states (Playing, Paused, Stopped, Buffering)

Command Pattern ⭐⭐
Encapsulates requests as objects. Useful for audio command queues.

Strategy Pattern ⭐⭐
Select algorithms at runtime. Useful for audio processing (EQ, effects)

Adapter Pattern ⭐⭐
Integrate different audio codec APIs with unified interface

